04806nam a22009375i 9780520927285DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696461  a97805209272857 a10.1525/97805209272852doi  a(DE-B1597)520846  a(OCoLC)1096468709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aTX641 4aTX641b.A36 2002 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a641/.01/32211 aAlbala, Ken, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEating Right in the Renaissance /cKen Albala. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v20 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEating right has been an obsession for longer than we think. Renaissance Europe had its own flourishing tradition of dietary advice. Then, as now, an industry of experts churned out diet books for an eager and concerned public. Providing a cornucopia of information on food and an intriguing account of the differences between the nutritional logic of the past and our own time, this inviting book examines the wide-ranging dietary literature of the Renaissance. Ken Albala ultimately reveals the working of the Renaissance mind from a unique perspective: we come to understand a people through their ideas on food.Eating Right in the Renaissance takes us through an array of historical sources in a narrative that is witty and spiced with fascinating details. Why did early Renaissance writers recommend the herbs parsley, arugula, anise, and mint to fortify sexual prowess? Why was there such a strong outcry against melons and cucumbers, even though people continued to eat them in large quantities? Why was wine considered a necessary nutrient? As he explores these and other questions, Albala explains the history behind Renaissance dietary theories; the connections among food, exercise, and sex; the changing relationship between medicine and cuisine; and much more. Whereas modern nutritionists may promise a slimmer waistline, more stamina, or freedom from disease, Renaissance food writers had entirely different ideas about the value of eating right. As he uncovers these ideas from the past, Ken Albala puts our own dietary obsessions in an entirely new light in this elegantly written and often surprising new chapter on the history of food.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFood habitszEuropexHistory. 0aGastronomy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aanise.  aaphrodisiacs.  aarugula.  acucumbers.  adangerous food.  adietary advice.  adiets.  aeurope.  aeuropean history.  afolk medicine.  afood and nutrition.  afood and sex.  afood culture.  afood history.  afood medicine.  afood studies.  aherbs.  ahistoric food research.  ahistorical diets.  amelons.  amint.  anonfiction.  anutrition.  anutritional anthropology.  aparsley.  arenaissance culture.  arenaissance food.  arenaissance history.  arenaissance life.  arenaissance.  asexual prowess.  awine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092728540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520927285/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles